00:25:42,767 --> 00:25:45,033
- I'm not the one who's
getting confused.

527
00:25:47,700 --> 00:25:49,300
- So, how come you
didn't run away from home

528
00:25:49,333 --> 00:25:50,367
and join the Navy?

529
00:25:50,400 --> 00:25:53,200
- Couldn't stand all that
yes, sir, no, sir stuff.

530
00:25:53,233 --> 00:25:55,033
- Sammi was always
Daddy's favorite.

531
00:25:55,067 --> 00:25:56,833
He taught her how to play pool.

532
00:25:56,867 --> 00:25:58,800
- Dad's a real hustler, huh?

533
00:25:58,833 --> 00:26:00,433
Amazing the way parents
operate on kids

534
00:26:00,467 --> 00:26:01,600
and kids on each other.

535
00:26:04,633 --> 00:26:05,800
Seen a lot of those
kind of games,

536
00:26:05,833 --> 00:26:07,433
putting one kid
against the other.

537
00:26:11,133 --> 00:26:12,567
- A dollar she makes it.

538
00:26:12,600 --> 00:26:14,500
- You're on.

539
00:26:14,533 --> 00:26:16,300
- Do you mind?

540
00:26:16,333 --> 00:26:17,200
- $2.

541
00:26:19,733 --> 00:26:20,733
- You're on.

542
00:26:24,400 --> 00:26:25,233
- Oh.

543
00:26:25,267 --> 00:26:26,733
Nah, I put her off.

544
00:26:26,767 --> 00:26:28,467
She's really good.

545
00:26:28,500 --> 00:26:31,167
Daddy used to make us play
all the time for money.

546
00:26:31,200 --> 00:26:33,333
- I feel like I know him
without ever having met him.

547
00:26:33,367 --> 00:26:35,533
- Kim exaggerates everything.

548
00:26:35,567 --> 00:26:38,567
(suspenseful music)

549
00:26:48,433 --> 00:26:53,200
- How come you still call her
by your father's pet name?

550
00:26:56,733 --> 00:26:58,567
Suggests to me you
haven't accepted Theresa

551
00:26:58,600 --> 00:26:59,700
for who she really is.

552
00:27:04,300 --> 00:27:05,800
Want a little bet on this one,
Sammi?

553
00:27:05,833 --> 00:27:07,167
Remind you of childhood.

554
00:27:11,533 --> 00:27:15,000
- Five bucks a game,
best of 10, loser breaks.

555
00:27:18,433 --> 00:27:20,100
- It's what Daddy liked to bet.

556
00:27:23,233 --> 00:27:24,467
- Shoot pool, big sister.

557
00:27:28,633 --> 00:27:32,000
(pool balls clacking)

558
00:27:39,100 --> 00:27:40,400
You hustled me, didn't you?

559
00:27:42,867 --> 00:27:44,067
- Well, kind of.

560
00:27:46,167 --> 00:27:47,033
You mind?

561
00:27:50,467 --> 00:27:51,633
(both laugh)

562
00:27:51,667 --> 00:27:53,400
- You're pretty smooth.

563
00:27:54,767 --> 00:27:55,600
I like that.

564
00:27:55,633 --> 00:27:57,167
You take care of Theresa,
can't you?

565
00:27:57,200 --> 00:27:58,500
- [Kim] Yeah.

566
00:27:58,533 --> 00:28:00,333
- You're not looking for
somebody else to do it for you.

567
00:28:00,367 --> 00:28:02,400
- Is that how it was with Cindy?

568
00:28:05,633 --> 00:28:07,067
- Something like that.

569
00:28:15,433 --> 00:28:18,233
(engine revving)

570
00:28:23,233 --> 00:28:25,767
(subdued music)

571
00:28:34,100 --> 00:28:38,100
- Of course, if you don't
want to talk about it.

572
00:28:55,833 --> 00:28:56,667
- You coming in?

573
00:29:01,567 --> 00:29:04,367
- David, I'm not ready
for a physical thing.

574
00:29:04,400 --> 00:29:05,300
It's not you.

575
00:29:06,600 --> 00:29:08,167
It's something that happened.

576
00:29:08,200 --> 00:29:09,133
- You don't have to explain.

577
00:29:09,167 --> 00:29:09,733
It's okay.

578
00:29:11,200 --> 00:29:12,333
You don't have to worry.

579
00:29:13,767 --> 00:29:16,633
I don't want what you
don't want to give.

580
00:29:20,233 --> 00:29:21,267
- [Kim] Some place.

581
00:29:22,267 --> 00:29:24,067
You a survivalist, or what?

582
00:29:24,100 --> 00:29:27,167
- [David] (laughs) Well,
I'm surviving so far.

583
00:29:28,100 --> 00:29:28,933
- And that's enough for you.

584
00:29:28,967 --> 00:29:30,167
- Hey, don't knock it
till you try it.

585
00:29:30,200 --> 00:29:32,600
You go from home, to the Navy,
to living with your sister.

586
00:29:32,633 --> 00:29:34,667
That's not taking too
many chances.

587
00:29:34,700 --> 00:29:36,233
- And you, too.

588
00:29:36,267 --> 00:29:38,700
- I live every day like
someone's sneaking up behind me.

589
00:29:38,733 --> 00:29:41,333
So, I practice every day
sneaking up behind them.

590
00:29:41,367 --> 00:29:42,267
Cheers.

591
00:29:46,767 --> 00:29:48,633
- So, were you very
much in love with Cindy?

592
00:29:48,667 --> 00:29:51,333
- Whoa, you don't give up,
do you?

593
00:29:51,367 --> 00:29:52,233
- [Kim] No, sir.

594
00:29:54,733 --> 00:29:58,067
- I created Cynthia,
or I tried to.

595
00:29:58,100 --> 00:30:00,800
I was in love with what
she was gonna become.

596
00:30:00,833 --> 00:30:02,167
- [Kim] Doesn't
sound too loving.

597
00:30:03,367 --> 00:30:06,233
- When I first met Cindy,
she weighed about 200 pounds,

598
00:30:06,267 --> 00:30:09,167
had greasy hair, complexion
like a glazed donut,

599
00:30:09,200 --> 00:30:10,800
and a nose like Pinocchio.

600
00:30:10,833 --> 00:30:12,267
She hated herself.

601
00:30:12,300 --> 00:30:13,500
I didn't blame her.

602
00:30:13,533 --> 00:30:15,633
- [Kim] So, why were you
attracted to her?

603
00:30:17,867 --> 00:30:20,300
- 'Cause I could feel the
pain coming off her in waves.

604
00:30:20,333 --> 00:30:22,233
She was like
radioactive with it.

605
00:30:23,467 --> 00:30:26,067
And I was interested in
why this ugly, fat chick

606
00:30:26,100 --> 00:30:27,400
was just so totally screwed up.

607
00:30:27,433 --> 00:30:28,367
- [Kim] Did you ask her?

608
00:30:28,400 --> 00:30:29,333
- Sure.

609
00:30:29,367 --> 00:30:30,567
I said, how come a fat,
ugly chick like you

610
00:30:30,600 --> 00:30:31,633
is so totally screwed up?

611
00:30:31,667 --> 00:30:33,033
- [Kim] What did she say?

612
00:30:33,867 --> 00:30:35,567
- Well, she said a
lot of things,

613
00:30:35,600 --> 00:30:38,500
but in the end it all
came down to one thing.

614
00:30:38,533 --> 00:30:42,067
Somebody was putting her down
and that person was Cindy.

615
00:30:42,100 --> 00:30:43,300
- [Kim] You said her father was

616
00:30:43,333 --> 00:30:44,733
terrible to her or something?

617
00:30:45,767 --> 00:30:47,433
- Her mother wasn't much better.

618
00:30:49,700 --> 00:30:51,500
But you can't blame
everything on your parents.

619
00:30:51,533 --> 00:30:53,233
It just doesn't solve
your problems.

620
00:30:53,267 --> 00:30:55,700
I told her, quit complaining.

621
00:30:55,733 --> 00:30:58,200
You're just giving away
your power to the past.

622
00:31:00,100 --> 00:31:04,233
So, I got her to stop
eating the crap she ate

623
00:31:04,267 --> 00:31:06,233
and got her to start
exercising, reading books,

624
00:31:06,267 --> 00:31:08,300
you know, to clean out her mind.

625
00:31:08,333 --> 00:31:09,400
Put her in touch with her gift.

626
00:31:09,433 --> 00:31:12,367
She was a natural psychic.

627
00:31:13,400 --> 00:31:14,200
She didn't know it.

628
00:31:14,233 --> 00:31:16,233
She knew stuff before
it happened,

629
00:31:16,267 --> 00:31:17,633
but she never figured why.

630
00:31:20,267 --> 00:31:22,300
I even got her to get
her nose fixed.

631
00:31:23,767 --> 00:31:25,067
Turned out pretty good.

632
00:31:26,667 --> 00:31:29,000
- [Kim] And were you
in love with her then?

633
00:31:39,433 --> 00:31:41,433
- I was trying to make her
into somebody like you,

634
00:31:41,467 --> 00:31:44,400
but I just didn't have
the blueprint.

635
00:31:46,100 --> 00:31:48,700
- Well, there's only one
of those and I have it.

636
00:31:48,733 --> 00:31:49,600
- I know.

637
00:31:54,500 --> 00:31:56,200
I know.

638
00:31:56,233 --> 00:31:58,733
(subdued music)

639
00:32:02,667 --> 00:32:05,600
- David is a person of
deep feelings

640
00:32:05,633 --> 00:32:08,600
and considerable sensitivity.

641
00:32:08,633 --> 00:32:13,167
He has expressed a remarkable
degree of affection for me

642
00:32:13,200 --> 00:32:17,233
and indeed may be in the process
of falling in love with me.

643
00:32:20,067 --> 00:32:21,200
Now listen.

644
00:32:21,233 --> 00:32:23,533
This is the one time, first
and last, I'm telling you.

645
00:32:23,567 --> 00:32:24,733
This client isn't paying
for you to get

646
00:32:24,767 --> 00:32:27,333
jugged up every night with
some sleazeball

647
00:32:27,367 --> 00:32:29,467
that's so hot to trot that
he tells you he loves you.

648
00:32:29,500 --> 00:32:31,067
If you think he's keeping
something hidden

649
00:32:31,100 --> 00:32:33,167
about the Campbell
killings, that's one thing.

650
00:32:33,200 --> 00:32:35,367
But I don't wanna hear
anything more

651
00:32:35,400 --> 00:32:37,333
about this Dear Abby soap opera.

652
00:32:43,100 --> 00:32:45,400
(hand slams)

653
00:32:50,633 --> 00:32:53,100
- Aw, to hell with them
and their agency.

654
00:32:53,133 --> 00:32:55,333
I survived before this,
I'll survive after it.

655
00:32:55,367 --> 00:32:57,667
They're all so damn scared
of the old tone, you know?

656
00:32:57,700 --> 00:33:00,167
They all think they're the ones
who know how to handle this.

657
00:33:00,200 --> 00:33:02,400
I am the only one who could've
got this close to David.

658
00:33:02,433 --> 00:33:03,433
Don't they get that?

659
00:33:04,767 --> 00:33:06,200
- You love it.

660
00:33:06,233 --> 00:33:07,533
You just love it.

661
00:33:07,567 --> 00:33:09,033
All this playacting.

662
00:33:09,067 --> 00:33:10,733
Miss Undercover, USA.

663
00:33:10,767 --> 00:33:12,133
- What is your problem?

664
00:33:12,167 --> 00:33:13,133
- You love making up lies.

665
00:33:13,167 --> 00:33:14,533
You love believing 'em.

666
00:33:14,567 --> 00:33:15,667
- You're supposed to
be my friend.

667
00:33:15,700 --> 00:33:17,100
I don't need this from you.

668
00:33:17,133 --> 00:33:19,800
- I am your friend
and I know you

669
00:33:19,833 --> 00:33:21,533
which is more than you
do right now.

670
00:33:21,567 --> 00:33:22,833
You're getting involved
with this creep, aren't you?

671
00:33:22,867 --> 00:33:24,333
- How do you know he's a creep?

672
00:33:24,367 --> 00:33:26,367
You hustled him at pool,
that's what you know.

673
00:33:26,400 --> 00:33:28,600
You don't know what it's
like being somebody else,

674
00:33:28,633 --> 00:33:31,300
being seen as somebody else,
feeling like somebody else.

675
00:33:31,333 --> 00:33:32,333
- Answer the question, Kim.

676
00:33:32,367 --> 00:33:33,833
- You promised to
call me Theresa.

677
00:33:33,867 --> 00:33:35,567
- Answer the question, Theresa.

678
00:33:35,600 --> 00:33:38,433
- That's the way it works
for me and it's working.

679
00:33:38,467 --> 00:33:39,700
I'm getting close to him.

680
00:33:41,467 --> 00:33:42,367
- You slept with him yet?

681
00:33:42,400 --> 00:33:44,133
- No, I haven't.

682
00:33:44,167 --> 00:33:45,733
And he hasn't pushed me, either.

683
00:33:45,767 --> 00:33:46,600
He--

684
00:33:46,633 --> 00:33:48,633
- Oh, respects you.

685
00:33:48,667 --> 00:33:49,700
- Yeah, as a matter of fact.

686
00:33:49,733 --> 00:33:51,533
I think he does.

687
00:33:51,567 --> 00:33:53,233
- Aw, sweet.

688
00:33:59,600 --> 00:34:02,233
(tense music)

689
00:34:13,067 --> 00:34:13,733
- David?

690
00:34:17,067 --> 00:34:17,700
David?

691
00:34:24,133 --> 00:34:25,000
David?

692
00:34:26,433 --> 00:34:27,700
David, you here?

693
00:34:48,833 --> 00:34:50,433
David, it's me.

694
00:34:50,467 --> 00:34:53,233
(knocks on door)

695
00:35:18,233 --> 00:35:20,500
(dramatic music)

696
00:35:20,533 --> 00:35:23,433
- Bang-bang.
(Kim yells)

697
00:35:23,467 --> 00:35:24,400
- Damn it, David.

698
00:35:24,433 --> 00:35:25,667
Don't do that.

699
00:35:25,700 --> 00:35:27,067
Don't ever do that.

700
00:35:27,100 --> 00:35:28,233
- You didn't hear me coming,
did you?

701
00:35:28,267 --> 00:35:30,067
- I think that sort
of thing sucks.

702
00:35:40,567 --> 00:35:42,033
- I'm not gonna hurt you.

703
00:35:42,067 --> 00:35:43,233
- How do I know that?

704
00:35:45,867 --> 00:35:46,633
- Why?

705
00:35:47,667 --> 00:35:49,200
Why do you think I
might hurt you?

706
00:35:49,233 --> 00:35:50,133
- I...

707
00:35:52,833 --> 00:35:54,000
It's not you.

708
00:35:54,833 --> 00:35:55,700
- Well, who is it?

709
00:35:57,367 --> 00:35:59,067
- You scared me, okay?

710
00:35:59,100 --> 00:35:59,800
Fine, all right?

711
00:35:59,833 --> 00:36:00,667
You scared me.

712
00:36:10,567 --> 00:36:13,367
- There's something you're
not telling me, Theresa.

713
00:36:13,400 --> 00:36:15,633
You can tell me anything.

714
00:36:24,133 --> 00:36:26,800
- About a year ago, I was raped.

715
00:36:26,833 --> 00:36:28,133
It was partly my fault.

716
00:36:29,067 --> 00:36:31,600
(subdued music)

717
00:36:31,633 --> 00:36:34,700
I ran out of gas, and I
was walking to get some,

718
00:36:34,733 --> 00:36:36,200
and a car came by.

719
00:36:37,133 --> 00:36:38,667
It was kind of in the country.

720
00:36:38,700 --> 00:36:39,733
Two guys were in it.

721
00:36:42,233 --> 00:36:44,433
They asked me if I
wanted a lift, I said no.

722
00:36:46,667 --> 00:36:49,200
They said it was a couple
miles to the next gas station.

723
00:36:50,467 --> 00:36:53,067
He said, "What's the
matter, don't you trust us?"

724
00:36:53,100 --> 00:36:55,233
I said it wasn't that,
but I'd walk anyway.

725
00:36:58,633 --> 00:37:00,333
I was too close to the car.

726
00:37:03,200 --> 00:37:05,633
He grabbed my wrist and
they drove off.

727
00:37:07,533 --> 00:37:08,700
I had to run alongside.

728
00:37:11,433 --> 00:37:13,033
After a bit, I fell down.

729
00:37:16,100 --> 00:37:18,500
They stopped the car and
pulled me inside.

730
00:37:36,867 --> 00:37:39,300
- Well, that wasn't your fault.

731
00:37:42,233 --> 00:37:43,433
- I don't know.

732
00:37:43,467 --> 00:37:44,600
Dumb of me.

733
00:37:44,633 --> 00:37:46,500
- To run out of gas?

734
00:37:46,533 --> 00:37:47,200
- Yeah.

735
00:37:48,133 --> 00:37:50,267
I'm always doing dumb
things like that.

736
00:37:52,433 --> 00:37:55,333
- Rape isn't a punishment for
running out of gas, Theresa.

737
00:37:56,867 --> 00:37:58,167
Not even in Texas.

738
00:38:06,067 --> 00:38:07,000
- Then why?

739
00:38:09,700 --> 00:38:11,300
Why did it happen?

740
00:38:12,467 --> 00:38:14,100
Why did it happen?

741
00:38:16,567 --> 00:38:18,133
(Kim sobbing)

742
00:38:18,167 --> 00:38:20,467
- Because it is an awful
world we're in.

743
00:38:25,067 --> 00:38:28,467
I won't ever let that
happen to you again.

744
00:38:29,333 --> 00:38:30,233
Never.

745
00:38:32,700 --> 00:38:34,433
Never, never, never.

746
00:38:37,233 --> 00:38:40,400
- [Man] George, give me five
of these, will you please?

747
00:38:40,433 --> 00:38:41,600
(coin clanks)

748
00:38:41,633 --> 00:38:45,200
- I want a tuna melt on
rye and some iced tea.

749
00:38:45,233 --> 00:38:46,233
The money...

750
00:38:46,267 --> 00:38:47,233
(fist pounding)

751
00:38:47,267 --> 00:38:48,100
Gummit.

752
00:38:48,133 --> 00:38:49,833
The money's in my coat.

753
00:38:49,867 --> 00:38:50,733
- I'm buying.

754
00:38:52,533 --> 00:38:53,700
- Well, well.

755
00:38:53,733 --> 00:38:56,833
If it ain't Sam Spade
come a slummin'

756
00:38:56,867 --> 00:38:58,733
in his 500 buck threads.

757
00:38:58,767 --> 00:38:59,933
Tell me, Posey.

758
00:38:59,967 --> 00:39:03,833
How is the private enterprise
law enforcement business?

759
00:39:03,867 --> 00:39:07,367
- Well, it's up to taking
you to lunch, Halsey.

760
00:39:07,400 --> 00:39:08,600
- Yeah?

761
00:39:08,633 --> 00:39:10,633
Well, ain't that nice.

762
00:39:14,767 --> 00:39:15,800
I can't help it, Posey.

763
00:39:15,833 --> 00:39:18,633
I'm just not very partial
to private detectives.

764
00:39:19,600 --> 00:39:20,433
- That include me?

765
00:39:20,467 --> 00:39:21,600
- Oh, no.

766
00:39:21,633 --> 00:39:23,100
You know I got a
little soft spot

767
00:39:23,133 --> 00:39:25,033
in my heart for you, Posey.

768
00:39:25,067 --> 00:39:26,433
I guess it's on
account of that name

769
00:39:26,467 --> 00:39:27,833
you had to grow up with.

770
00:39:27,867 --> 00:39:29,333
Posey, Posey.

771
00:39:30,433 --> 00:39:31,600
How come you never changed it?

772
00:39:31,633 --> 00:39:33,400
- [Posey] You play the
cards you get, Dan.

773
00:39:33,433 --> 00:39:34,367
You play the cards you get.

774
00:39:34,400 --> 00:39:36,133
- No, don't give me that bull.

775
00:39:36,167 --> 00:39:38,700
Next thing you'll tell me
is it made a man out of you.

776
00:39:38,733 --> 00:39:39,600
- Oh, no.

777
00:39:39,633 --> 00:39:40,567
I wouldn't go that far.

778
00:39:40,600 --> 00:39:43,300
(both laugh)

779
00:39:43,333 --> 00:39:46,633
Dan, we've been working
on the Campbell case.

780
00:39:46,667 --> 00:39:47,667
I suppose you heard?

781
00:39:48,733 --> 00:39:50,067
On behalf of the family.

782
00:39:51,467 --> 00:39:53,300
- [Dan] What's that
costing the sucker?

783
00:39:53,333 --> 00:39:56,133
- Well, they thought the
Houston Police Department

784
00:39:56,167 --> 00:39:57,167
had kind of quit on 'em.

785
00:39:57,200 --> 00:39:57,967
- Hey, hey, hey.

